<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; border-top:3.00px double #000000">&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; border-top:3.00px double #000000">&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; border-top:3.00px double #000000">&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; border-top:3.00px double #000000">&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD>&nbsp;</TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:7%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">During the three months and six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, the ALLL decreased $8&nbsp;thousand
and $18&nbsp;thousand, respectively. For the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, the ALLL associated with the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">1-4</FONT> family real estate loan portfolio decreased $14&nbsp;thousand and was partially offset
by an $8&nbsp;thousand increase in the ALLL associated with construction loans. During the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, the ALLL associated with 1 - 4 family real estate loans, construction and land acquisition and development loans
decreased by $7&nbsp;thousand, $9&nbsp;thousand and $6&nbsp;thousand, respectively. The primary reason for the changes in the ALLL balances, both in total, and within the identified segments, is changes in applicable loan balances and the return of
one <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-performing</FONT> loan to performing status. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">34 </P>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">During the three and six months ending December&nbsp;31, 2018, the ALLL increased
$14&nbsp;thousand and $33&nbsp;thousand, respectively. For the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2018, the ALLL associated with 1 - 4 family real estate loans increased $10&nbsp;thousand and the ALLL associated with commercial loans increased
$7&nbsp;thousand. These increases were partially offset by a decrease of $4&nbsp;thousand in the ALLL associated with the construction loan segment. During the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2018, the ALLL associated with 1 - 4 family real
estate loans, land acquisition and development loans and commercial loans increased by $17&nbsp;thousand, $10&nbsp;thousand and $4&nbsp;thousand, respectively. The primary reason for the changes in the ALLL balances, both in total, and within the
identified segments, is changes in applicable loan balances. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:18pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The adjustable rate advances are not convertible or callable. The FHLB advances are secured
by the Company&#146;s FHLB stock, mortgage-backed and investment securities, and loans, and are subject to substantial prepayment penalties. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Company also utilized revolving and short-term FHLB advances. Short-term FHLB advances generally mature within 90 days, while
revolving FHLB advances may be repaid by the Company without penalty. The following table presents information regarding such advances as of December&nbsp;31, 2019 and June&nbsp;30, 2019: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">At December&nbsp;31, 2019, the Company had remaining borrowing capacity with the FHLB of approximately
$2.9&nbsp;million. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The FHLB advances are secured by the Company&#146;s FHLB stock, loans, and mortgage-backed and investment
securities held in safekeeping at the FHLB. FHLB advances are subject to substantial prepayment penalties. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Company also has a
$5&nbsp;million unsecured line of credit with a regional bank. Borrowings under this line of credit generally are repayable within seven days. At December&nbsp;31, 2019, no borrowings were outstanding on this unsecured line. </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:18pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="9%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><B>12.</B></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left"><B><U>FAIR VALUE MEASUREMENTS </U> </B></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Fair value is defined as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability in the principal or most
advantageous market for an asset or liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. GAAP established a fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the use of inputs used in valuation methodologies into the
following three levels: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>

<TD></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="3%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="90%"></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top">Level&nbsp;I:</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">
<P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Quoted&nbsp;prices&nbsp;are&nbsp;available&nbsp;in&nbsp;active&nbsp;markets&nbsp;for&nbsp;identical&nbsp;assets&nbsp;or&nbsp;liabilities&nbsp;as&nbsp;
of&nbsp;the&nbsp;reported&nbsp;date.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">
<TD HEIGHT="19"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="19" COLSPAN="2"></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top">Level&nbsp;II:</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Pricing inputs are other than the quoted prices in active markets, which are either directly or indirectly observable as of the
reported date. The nature of these assets and liabilities includes items for which quoted prices are available but traded less frequently and items that are fair-valued using other financial instruments, the parameters of which can be directly
observed.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">
<TD HEIGHT="19"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="19" COLSPAN="2"></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top">Level&nbsp;III:</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Assets and liabilities that have little to no pricing observability as of the reported date. These items do not have <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">two-way</FONT> markets and are measured using management&#146;s best estimate of fair value, where the inputs into the determination of fair value require significant management judgment or estimation.</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">36 </P>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><U>Assets Measured at Fair Value on a Recurring Basis </U></B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Investment Securities <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Available-for-Sale</FONT></FONT> </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Fair values for securities available for sale are determined by obtaining quoted prices on nationally recognized securities exchanges or
matrix pricing, which is a mathematical technique widely used in the industry to value debt securities without relying exclusively on quoted prices for the specific securities, but rather by relying on the securities&#146; relationship to other
benchmark quoted securities. The Company has no Level I or Level III investment securities. Level II investment securities were primarily comprised of investment-grade corporate bonds and U.S. dollar-denominated investment-grade corporate bonds of
large foreign issuers. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The following tables present the assets reported on a recurring basis on the Consolidated Balance Sheet at
their fair value as of December&nbsp;31, 2019 and June&nbsp;30, 2019, by level within the fair value hierarchy. As required by GAAP, financial assets and liabilities are classified in their entirety based on the lowest level of input that is
significant to the fair value measurement. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><A NAME="tx851326_7"></A>ITEM&nbsp;2. </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS FOR THE THREE AND SIX MONTHS ENDED DECEMBER&nbsp;31, 2019 </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>FORWARD LOOKING STATEMENTS </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">In the normal
course of business, we, in an effort to help keep our shareholders and the public informed about our operations, may from time to time issue or make certain statements, either in writing or orally, that are or contain forward-looking statements, as
that term is defined in the U.S. federal securities laws. Generally, these statements relate to business plans or strategies, projected or anticipated benefits from acquisitions made by or to be made by us, projections involving anticipated
revenues, earnings, profitability or other aspects of operating results or other future developments in our affairs or the industry in which we conduct business. Forward-looking statements may be identified by reference to a future period or periods
or by the use of forward-looking terminology such as &#147;anticipated,&#148; &#147;believe,&#148; &#148;expect,&#148; &#148;intend,&#148; &#147;plan,&#148; &#147;estimate&#148; or similar expressions. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Although we believe that the anticipated results or other expectations reflected in our forward-looking statements are based on
reasonable assumptions, we can give no assurance that those results or expectations will be attained. Forward-looking statements involve risks, uncertainties and assumptions (some of which are beyond our control), and as a result actual results may
differ materially from those expressed in forward-looking statements. Factors that could cause actual results to differ from forward-looking statements include, but are not limited to, the following, as well as those discussed elsewhere herein: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:14pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

produce expected deposit and loan growth and anticipated contributions to our earnings; </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:14pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">You should not put undue reliance on any forward-looking statements. Forward-looking
statements speak only as of the date they are made, and we undertake no obligation to update them in light of new or future events except to the extent required by federal securities laws. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>GENERAL </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">WVS Financial Corp. (the
&#147;Company&#148;) is the parent holding company of West View Savings Bank (&#147;West View&#148; or the &#147;Savings Bank&#148;). The Company was organized in July 1993 as a Pennsylvania-chartered unitary bank holding company and acquired 100%
of the common stock of the Savings Bank in November 1993. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">West View Savings Bank is a Pennsylvania-chartered, FDIC-insured stock
savings bank conducting business from six offices in the North Hills suburbs of Pittsburgh. The Savings Bank converted from the mutual to the stock form of ownership in November 1993. The Savings Bank had no subsidiaries at December&nbsp;31, 2019.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The operating results of the Company depend primarily upon its net interest income, which is determined by the difference between
income on interest-earning assets, principally loans, mortgage-backed securities and investment securities, and interest expense on interest-bearing liabilities, which consist primarily of deposits and borrowings. The Company&#146;s net income is
also affected by its provision for loan losses, as well as the level of its <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-interest</FONT> income, including loan fees and service charges, and its <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-interest</FONT> expenses,
such as compensation and employee benefits, income taxes, deposit insurance and occupancy costs. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>FINANCIAL CONDITION </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Company&#146;s assets totaled $355.2&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2019, as compared to $355.8&nbsp;million at June&nbsp;30,
2019. The $570&nbsp;thousand or 0.2% decrease in total assets was principally due to a $4.4&nbsp;million decrease in mortgage-backed securities and a $2.3&nbsp;million decrease in interest-earning demand deposits, partially offset by a
$5.3&nbsp;million increase in investment securities <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">available-for-sale</FONT></FONT> and a $752&nbsp;thousand increase in net loans receivable. The decrease in mortgage-backed
securities was principally due to repayments of principal totaling $4.4&nbsp;million and the decrease in interest-earning demand deposits is associated with changing liquidity needs of the Company. The increase in securities <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">available-for-sale</FONT></FONT> was primarily the result of purchases of floating rate investment-grade corporate bonds totaling $17.3&nbsp;million, partially offset by securities sales of
$9.1&nbsp;million and $3.3&nbsp;million of maturities and calls. The increase in net loans receivable was primarily attributable to an increase in the single-family owner occupied segment of the loan portfolio. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Company&#146;s total liabilities decreased $2.0&nbsp;million or 0.6% to $317.7&nbsp;million as of December&nbsp;31, 2019 from
$319.8&nbsp;million as of June&nbsp;30, 2019. The decrease in total liabilities was primarily comprised of a $2.8&nbsp;million or 4.0% decrease in FHLB short-term advances, which was partially offset by a $700&nbsp;thousand increase in total
deposits. Certificates of deposit (&#147;CDs&#148;) increased by $4.5&nbsp;million and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-interest</FONT> bearing demand and savings deposit declined $1.7&nbsp;million and $1.0&nbsp;million, respectively, as of
December&nbsp;31, 2019 from June&nbsp;30, 2019. Management believes that the decrease in <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-interest</FONT> bearing demand deposits was primarily the result of seasonal fluctuations related to local real estate tax
collectors&#146; deposits. The increase in certificates of deposit was largely due to higher levels of brokered CDs as part of the Company&#146;s overall funding strategy. See also Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosures About Market Risk
&#147;Asset and Liability Management&#148;. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Total stockholders&#146; equity increased $1.5&nbsp;million or 4.1% to
$37.5&nbsp;million as of December&nbsp;31, 2019, from $36.0&nbsp;million as of June&nbsp;30, 2019. The increase in stockholders&#146; equity was primarily attributable to net income of $1.5&nbsp;million, which was partially offset by cash dividends
totaling $354&nbsp;thousand. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">41 </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>RESULTS OF OPERATIONS </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><B>General</B>. WVS Financial Corp. reported net income of $727&nbsp;million or $0.41 per share (diluted and basic) for the three months
ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 as compared to $685&nbsp;thousand or $0.38 per share for the same period in 2018. The $42&nbsp;thousand or 6.1% increase in net income during the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to a
$12&nbsp;thousand increase in <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-interest</FONT> income, a decrease in <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-interest</FONT> expense of $84&nbsp;thousand and a $22&nbsp;thousand decrease in the provision for loan
losses, which were partially offset by a $74&nbsp;thousand decrease in net interest income, when compared to the same period of 2018. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Net income for the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 totaled $1.5&nbsp;million or $0.86 per share (diluted and basic) as compared
to $1.4&nbsp;million or $0.80 per diluted share for the same period in 2018. The $88&nbsp;thousand or 6.1% increase in net income during the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to a $138&nbsp;thousand decrease in <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-interest</FONT> expense and a $51&nbsp;thousand decrease in the provision for loan losses, partially offset by a $71&nbsp;thousand decrease in net interest income and a $42&nbsp;thousand increase in income tax expense,
when compared to the same period in 2018. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><B>Net Interest Income</B>. The Company&#146;s net interest income decreased by
$74&nbsp;thousand or 4.3% for the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, when compared to the same period in 2018. The decrease in net interest income during the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was attributable to a $172&nbsp;thousand
decrease in interest income, partially offset by a $98&nbsp;thousand decrease in interest expense for the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, when compared to the same period in 2018. The decrease in interest income for the three months ended
December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to lower market yields earned on the Company&#146;s floating rate investment and mortgage-backed securities portfolio and lower average balances of mortgage-backed securities outstanding which were
partially offset by higher yields on Federal Home Loan Bank (&#147;FHLB&#148;) stock, and higher average balances of investment securities, loans and certificates of deposit when compared to the same period in 2018. The decrease in interest expense
for the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to lower rates paid on FHLB short-term and variable rate long-term borrowings and lower average balances of FHLB short-term borrowings, which were partially offset by
higher average balances of wholesale time deposits and higher rates paid on time deposits when compared to the same period in 2018. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">For the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, net interest income decreased $71&nbsp;thousand or 2.0% when compared to the same
period in 2018. The decrease in net interest income was primarily attributable to a $16&nbsp;thousand decrease in interest income and a $55&nbsp;thousand increase in interest expense for the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, when compared to
the same period in 2018. The decrease in interest income was primarily the result of lower average yields on the Company&#146;s floating rate investment and mortgage-backed securities, and lower outstanding balances of floating rate mortgage-backed
securities partially offset by higher average outstanding balances of loans and investment securities, and higher yields earned on FHLB stock, when compared to the same period in 2018. The increase in interest expense was primarily attributable to
higher average balances outstanding of wholesale time deposits and higher yields paid on time deposits which were partially offset by lower yields paid on FHLB advances and lower average balances of FHLB advances outstanding during the six months
ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, when compared to the same period of 2018. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><B>Interest Income.</B><B> </B>Interest income on net loans
receivable increased $46&nbsp;thousand or 5.6% and $126&nbsp;thousand or 7.7% for the three and six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, respectively, when compared to the same periods in 2018. The increase for the three and six months ended
December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to increases of $5.1&nbsp;million and $5.4&nbsp;million, respectively, in the average balance of net loans receivable when compared to the same periods in 2018. For both the quarter and six months
ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, the increase in the average balance of loans outstanding was primarily attributable to loan originations and purchases in excess of repayments on new loans originated when compared to the same periods in 2018. During
fiscal 2018, 2019 and into fiscal 2020, the Company enjoyed higher demand for single-family home purchase loans. Substantially all of our loan originations and purchases were fixed-rate loans with a mix of 15, 20, and 30 year terms. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">42 </P>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Interest income on investment securities decreased $69&nbsp;thousand or 6.5% and
$10&nbsp;thousand or 0.5% for the three and six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, respectively, when compared to the same periods in 2018. The decrease for the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to a 37 basis
point decrease in the weighted average yield on investment securities, partially offset by a $7.5&nbsp;million increase in the average balance of investment securities outstanding, when compared to the same period in 2018. The decrease for the six
months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to a decrease in the weighted average yield of 13 basis points, partially offset by a $5.0&nbsp;million increase in the average balance of investment securities outstanding, when
compared to the same period in 2018. The increase in the average balance of investments outstanding during both periods is attributable to the redeployment of mortgage-backed securities cash flows into floating rate corporate bonds. The decrease in
weighted average yields in 2019 was principally attributable to lower three-month dollar London Interbank Offered Rates (&#147;LIBOR&#148;) when compared to the same periods in 2018. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Interest income on mortgage-backed securities decreased $170&nbsp;thousand or 18.3% and $174&nbsp;thousand or 9.6% for the three and six
months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, respectively, when compared to the same periods in 2018. The decrease for the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to the $5.3&nbsp;million decrease in the average balance of U.S.
Government agency mortgage-backed securities and a 47 basis point decrease in the weighted average yield earned on these securities. The decrease for the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was also primarily attributable to $5.6&nbsp;million
decline in the average balance of U.S. Government agency mortgage-backed securities and a 15 basis point decrease in the weighted average yield earned on these mortgage-backed securities, when compared to the same period in 2018. The decrease in the
average balances of U.S. Government and agency private-label mortgage-backed securities during the three and six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was attributable to principal pay downs during the periods. The mortgage-backed securities proceeds
during both periods were primarily used to fund purchases of floating rate corporate bonds in the investment portfolio and loan originations and purchases. The decrease in weighted average yields in 2019 was primarily attributable to higher <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-month</FONT> LIBOR when compared to the same periods in 2018. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Dividend income on FHLB stock
increased $14&nbsp;thousand or 12.1% and $24&nbsp;thousand or 10.5% for the three and six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, respectively, when compared to the same periods in 2018. The change in dividends on FHLB stock for both the three and six
months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable by a 96 basis point increase in the average yield on FHLB stock held during the three and six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, when compared to the same periods in 2018. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Interest income on bank certificates of deposit increased $12&nbsp;thousand and $25&nbsp;thousand for the three and six months ended
December&nbsp;31, 2019, respectively, when compared to the same period in 2018. The increases in both periods of 2019 were primarily attributable to increases in the average portfolio balances of certificates of deposit of approximately
$2.0&nbsp;million. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><B>Interest Expense.</B><B> </B>Interest paid on FHLB variable-rate long-term advances and FHLB short-term
advances decreased by $74&nbsp;thousand and $127&nbsp;thousand, respectively, for the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, when compared to the same period in 2018. For the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, the decrease in interest
expense on the FHLB variable-rate long-term advances was principally due to lower market interest rates, when compared to the same period in 2018. The decrease in interest expense on FHLB short-term advances for the three months ended
December&nbsp;31, 2019 reflects lower market interest rates as well as a $5.5&nbsp;million decrease in the average balance of advances outstanding, when compared to the same period in 2018. Interest expense on FHLB short-term borrowings during the
six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 decreased by $732&nbsp;thousand or 54.4% primarily due to a decrease of $57.9&nbsp;million in the average balance of advances outstanding, when compared to the same period of 2018. For the six months ended
December&nbsp;31, 2019, interest expense on both FHLB long-term fixed and long-term variable FHLB advances increased by $116&nbsp;thousand or 100.0% and $441&nbsp;thousand or 83.8%, respectively, when compared to the same period in 2018. These
increases were primarily due to higher average balances of FHLB long-term advances outstanding during the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, when compared to the same period in 2018. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">43 </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Interest expense on deposits increased $103&nbsp;thousand or 79.8% and $230&nbsp;thousand
or 91.3% for the three and six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, respectively, when compared to the same periods in 2018. The increase in interest expense on deposits for the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to
a 59 basis point increase in the weighted average rate paid on time deposits and a $14.3&nbsp;million increase in the average balance of time deposits, when compared to the same period in 2018. For the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, the
$230&nbsp;thousand increase in interest expense was primarily due to a 55 basis point increase in the weighted average rate paid on time deposits and a $14.6&nbsp;million increase in the average balance of the time deposits, when compared to the
same period in 2018. The increases in the average balances of time deposits for both the three and six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, were primarily attributable to higher levels of short-term brokered deposits when compared to the same
periods of 2018. From time to time the Company uses brokered deposits to fund investment purchases or as an alternative to FHLB borrowings if the cost of such deposits is less than other wholesale funding options. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><B>Provision for Loan Losses</B>. A provision for loan losses is charged or accreted to earnings to bring the total allowance to a level
considered adequate by management to absorb potential losses in the portfolio. Management&#146;s determination of the adequacy of the allowance is based on an evaluation of the portfolio considering past experience, current economic conditions,
volume, growth and composition of the loan portfolio, and other relevant factors. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">During the three and six months ending
December&nbsp;31, 2019, the allowance for loan losses (&#147;ALLL&#148;) decreased $8&nbsp;thousand and $18&nbsp;thousand, respectively. For the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, the ALLL associated with 1 - 4 family real estate loans
decreased $14&nbsp;thousand and the ALLL associated with construction loans increased $8&nbsp;thousand. During the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, the ALLL associated with 1 - 4 family real estate loans, construction land acquisition and
development loans decreased by $7&nbsp;thousand, $9&nbsp;thousand and $6&nbsp;thousand, respectively. The primary reason for the changes in the ALLL balances, both in total, and within the identified segments, are changes in applicable loan balances
and the return of one <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-performing</FONT> loan to performing status. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">At December&nbsp;31, 2019,
the Company&#146;s total allowance for loan losses amounted to $530&nbsp;thousand or 0.58% of the Company&#146;s total loan portfolio, as compared to $548&nbsp;thousand or 0.60% at June&nbsp;30, 2019. At December&nbsp;31, 2019, the Company had no <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-performing</FONT> loans as compared to $225&nbsp;thousand at June&nbsp;30, 2019. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><B><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Interest</FONT> Income</B>. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-interest</FONT> income increased $12&nbsp;thousand or 10.9% for the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, when compared to the same period in 2018.
The increase for the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to a $32&nbsp;thousand gain on the sale of investment securities and a $4&nbsp;thousand increase in service charges on deposits which were offset by a
$16&nbsp;thousand increase in other than temporary impairment losses on private label mortgage-backed securities, a $7&nbsp;thousand decrease in automated teller machine (ATM) program income and a $1&nbsp;thousand decrease in earnings on Bank-owned
life insurance, when compared to the same period in 2018. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">For the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-interest</FONT> income increased $12&nbsp;thousand or 5.5%, when compared to the same period in 2018. The increase in <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-interest</FONT> income for the six months ended
December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to a $34&nbsp;thousand gain on the sale of investment securities and a $5&nbsp;thousand increase in service charges on deposits, which were offset by an $18&nbsp;thousand increase in other than
temporary impairment losses on private label mortgage-backed securities, a $7&nbsp;thousand decrease in ATM program income and a $2&nbsp;thousand decrease in earnings on Bank-owned life insurance, when compared to the same period in 2018. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><B><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Interest</FONT> Expense</B>. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-interest</FONT> expense
decreased $84&nbsp;thousand or 8.8% for the three months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, when compared to the same period in 2018. The decrease in <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-interest</FONT> expense for the three months ended
December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to a $30&nbsp;thousand decrease in employee benefit costs, a $22&nbsp;thousand decrease in federal deposit insurance expense, $20&nbsp;thousand decrease in a variety of other operating expenses and a
$7&nbsp;thousand decrease in ATM network expenses, when compared to the same period in 2018. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-interest</FONT> expense decreased $138&nbsp;thousand or 7.4% for the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, when
compared to the same period in 2018. The decrease in <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-interest</FONT> expense for the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 was primarily attributable to a </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">44 </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">
$73&nbsp;thousand decrease in federal deposit insurance expense, a $41&nbsp;thousand decrease in employee benefit expense and a $21&nbsp;thousand decrease in ATM network expense, when compared to
the same period in 2018. The decrease in federal deposit insurance expense for both periods in 2019 was primarily attributable to the application of Small Bank Assessment Credits by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><B>Income Tax Expense. </B>Income tax expense increased $2&nbsp;thousand and $42&nbsp;thousand for the three and six months ended
December&nbsp;31, 2019, respectively, when compared to the same periods in 2018. The increases for both periods ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, were primarily due higher levels of taxable income when compared to the same periods of 2018. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>LIQUIDITY AND CAPITAL RESOURCES </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Net cash
provided by operating activities totaled $1.8&nbsp;million during the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019. Net cash provided by operating activities was primarily comprised of net income of $1.5&nbsp;million and a $167&nbsp;thousand decrease in
accrued interest receivable. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Funds used for investing activities totaled $608&nbsp;thousand during the six months ended
December&nbsp;31, 2019. Primary uses of funds during this period were purchases of investment securities available for sale totaling $17.3&nbsp;million, purchases of loans totaling $6.3&nbsp;million and purchases of certificates of deposit totaling
$1.3&nbsp;million. Primary sources of funds during the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 included proceeds from repayments of investment securities and mortgage-backed securities in the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">held-to-maturity</FONT></FONT> portfolio totaling $500&nbsp;thousand and $4.4&nbsp;million, respectively, proceeds from repayments of investment securities in the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">available-for-sale</FONT></FONT> portfolio totaling $3.3&nbsp;million, $9.1&nbsp;million of proceeds on sales of investment securities available for sale and repayments of loans in excess of originations of
$5.6&nbsp;million and $1.6&nbsp;million of proceeds from maturing certificates of deposit. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Funds used for financing activities
totaled $2.6&nbsp;million for the six months ended December&nbsp;31, 2019. The primary uses were a $2.8&nbsp;million decrease in FHLB short-term advances, a $3.2&nbsp;million decrease in transaction and savings accounts, a $618&nbsp;thousand
decrease in advance payments by borrowers for taxes and insurance and $354&nbsp;thousand in cash dividends paid on the Company&#146;s common stock, which were partially offset by increases in certificates of deposits totaling $4.5&nbsp;million.
Management believes that a significant portion of our local maturing deposits will remain with the Company. Management has determined that it currently is maintaining adequate liquidity and continues to match funding sources with lending and
investment opportunities. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Company&#146;s primary sources of funds are deposits, amortization, repayments and maturities of
existing loans, mortgage-backed securities and investment securities, funds from operations, and funds obtained through FHLB advances and other borrowings. Certificates of deposit scheduled to mature in one year or less at December&nbsp;31, 2019
totaled $38.7&nbsp;million including $14.7&nbsp;million of maturing wholesale time deposits. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Historically, the Company used its
sources of funds primarily to meet its ongoing commitments to pay maturing savings certificates and savings withdrawals, fund loan commitments and maintain a substantial portfolio of investment securities. At December&nbsp;31, 2019, total approved
loan commitments outstanding were $2.6&nbsp;million. At the same date, commitments under unused lines of credit amounted to $5.1&nbsp;million and the unadvanced portion of construction loans approximated $3.6&nbsp;million. The Company has been able
to generate sufficient cash through the retail deposit market, its traditional funding source, and through FHLB advances, and other wholesale funding sources, to provide the cash utilized in investing activities. The Company&#146;s available for
sale segment of the investment portfolio totaled $138.1&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2019. In addition the Company had $1.6&nbsp;million of certificates of deposit at December&nbsp;31, 2019. Management believes that the Company currently has
adequate liquidity available to respond to liquidity demands. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">On January&nbsp;27, 2020, the Company&#146;s Board of Directors
declared a quarterly cash dividend of $0.10 per share, payable on February&nbsp;20, 2020, to shareholders of record at the close of business on February&nbsp;10, 2020. Dividends are subject to determination and declaration by the Board of Directors,
which take into </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">45 </P>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">
account the Company&#146;s financial condition, statutory and regulatory restrictions, general economic conditions and other factors. There can be no assurance that dividends will in fact be paid
on the Common Stock in future periods or that, if paid, such dividends will not be reduced or eliminated. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">As of December&nbsp;31,
2019, WVS Financial Corp. maintained Common Equity Tier I Capital, Tier I, and total risk-based capital equal to $37.2&nbsp;million or 19.1%, $37.2&nbsp;million or 19.1%, and $37.7&nbsp;million or 19.4%, respectively, of total risk-weighted assets,
and Tier I leverage capital of $37.2&nbsp;million or 10.4% of average quarterly assets. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Nonperforming assets consist of nonaccrual
loans and real estate owned. A loan is placed on nonaccrual status when, in the judgment of management, the probability of collection of interest is deemed insufficient to warrant further accrual. When a loan is placed on nonaccrual status,
previously accrued but uncollected interest is deducted from interest income. The Company normally does not accrue interest on loans past due 90 days or more, however, interest may be accrued if management believes that it will collect on the loan.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Company had no nonperforming assets at December&nbsp;31, 2019 compared to $225&nbsp;thousand or 0.06% of total assets at
June&nbsp;30, 2019. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">During the quarter ended September&nbsp;30, 2019, the Company&#146;s one nonperforming single-family real
estate loan was discharged from bankruptcy and since that time has been current. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">46 </P>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><B><A NAME="tx851326_8"></A>ITEM&nbsp;3.</B></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="justify"><B></B></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><B>QUANTITATIVE AND QUALITATIVE DISCLOSURES ABOUT MARKET RISK </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><B>ASSET AND LIABILITY MANAGEMENT </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Company&#146;s primary market risk exposure is interest rate risk and, to a lesser extent, liquidity risk. All of the Company&#146;s
transactions are denominated in US dollars with no specific foreign exchange exposure. The Savings Bank has no agricultural loan assets and therefore would not have a specific exposure to changes in commodity prices. Any impacts that changes in
foreign exchange rates and commodity prices would have on interest rates are assumed to be exogenous and will be analyzed on an <U>ex</U> <U>post</U> basis. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Interest rate risk (&#147;IRR&#148;) is the exposure of a banking organization&#146;s financial condition to adverse movements in
interest rates. Accepting this risk can be an important source of profitability and shareholder value, however excessive levels of IRR can pose a significant threat to the Company&#146;s earnings and capital base. Accordingly, effective risk
management that maintains IRR at prudent levels is essential to the Company&#146;s safety and soundness. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Evaluating a financial
institution&#146;s exposure to changes in interest rates includes assessing both the adequacy of the management process used to control IRR and the organization&#146;s quantitative level of exposure. When assessing the IRR management process, the
Company seeks to ensure that appropriate policies, procedures, management information systems and internal controls are in place to maintain IRR at prudent levels with consistency and continuity. Evaluating the quantitative level of IRR exposure
requires the Company to assess the existing and potential future effects of changes in interest rates on its consolidated financial condition, including capital adequacy, earnings, liquidity, and, where appropriate, asset quality. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Financial institutions derive their income primarily from the excess of interest collected over interest paid. The rates of interest an
institution earns on its assets and owes on its liabilities generally are established contractually for a period of time. Since market interest rates change over time, an institution is exposed to lower profit margins (or losses) if it cannot adapt
to interest-rate changes. For example, assume that an institution&#146;s assets carry intermediate- or long-term fixed rates and that those assets were funded with short-term liabilities. If market interest rates rise by the time the short-term
liabilities must be refinanced, the increase in the institution&#146;s interest expense on its liabilities may not be sufficiently offset if assets continue to earn at the long-term fixed rates. Accordingly, an institution&#146;s profits could
decrease on existing assets because the institution will either have lower net interest income or, possibly, net interest expense. Similar risks exist when assets are subject to contractual interest-rate ceilings, or rate sensitive assets are funded
by longer-term, fixed-rate liabilities in a decreasing-rate environment. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">During the fiscal years 2014 - 2019 and into fiscal year
2020, intermediate and long-term market interest rates fluctuated considerably. Many central banks, including the Federal Reserve, continued above normal levels of monetary accommodation including quantitative easing and targeted asset purchase
programs. The desired outcomes of these programs are to stimulate aggregate demand, reduce high levels of unemployment and to further lower market interest rates. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The effect of interest rate changes on a financial institution&#146;s assets and liabilities may be analyzed by examining the
&#147;interest rate sensitivity&#148; of the assets and liabilities and by monitoring an institution&#146;s interest rate sensitivity &#147;gap&#148;. An asset or liability is said to be interest rate sensitive within a specific time period if it
will mature or reprice within a given time period. A gap is considered positive (negative) when the amount of rate sensitive assets (liabilities) exceeds the amount of rate sensitive liabilities (assets). During a period of falling interest rates, a
negative gap would tend to result in an increase in net interest income. During a period of rising interest rates, a positive gap would tend to result in an increase in net interest income. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">47 </P>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">As part of its asset/liability management strategy, the Company maintained an asset
sensitive financial position due to unusually low market interest rates. An asset sensitive financial position may benefit earnings during a period of rising interest rates and reduce earnings during a period of declining interest rates. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The following table sets forth certain information at the dates indicated relating to the Company&#146;s interest-earning assets and
interest-bearing liabilities which are estimated to mature or are scheduled to reprice within one year. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Company utilizes an income simulation model to measure interest rate risk and to manage interest
rate sensitivity. The Company believes that income simulation modeling may enable the Company to better estimate the possible effects on net interest income due to changing market interest rates. Other key model parameters include: estimated
prepayment rates on the Company&#146;s loan, mortgage-backed securities and investment portfolios; savings decay rate assumptions; and the repayment terms and embedded options of the Company&#146;s borrowings. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">49 </P>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The following table presents the simulated impact of a 100 and 200 basis point upward or
downward (parallel) shift in market interest rates on net interest income, return on average equity, return on average assets and the market value of portfolio equity at December&nbsp;31, 2019. This analysis was done assuming that the
interest-earning assets will average approximately $348&nbsp;million and $350&nbsp;million over a projected twelve and twenty-four month period, respectively, for the estimated impact on change in net interest income, return on average equity and
return on average assets. The estimated changes in market value of equity were calculated using balance sheet levels at December&nbsp;31, 2019. Actual future results could differ materially from our estimates primarily due to unknown future interest
rate changes and the level of prepayments on our investment and loan portfolios. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><U>Analysis of Sensitivity to Changes in Market Interest Rates
</U></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>

<TD WIDTH="35%"></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD></TD>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">50 </P>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">In the ordinary course of its construction lending business, the Savings Bank enters into
performance standby letters of credit. Typically, the standby letters of credit are issued on behalf of a builder to a third party to ensure the timely completion of a certain aspect of a construction project or land development. At
December&nbsp;31, 2019, the Savings Bank had no performance standby letters of credit outstanding. In the event that an obligor is unable to perform its obligations as specified in the applicable letter of credit agreement, the Savings Bank would be
obligated to disburse funds up to the amount specified in the letter of credit agreement. The Savings Bank maintains adequate collateral that could be liquidated to fund these contingent obligations. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B><A NAME="tx851326_9"></A>ITEM&nbsp;4. CONTROLS AND PROCEDURES </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">As of December&nbsp;31, 2019, an evaluation was performed under the supervision and with the participation of the Company&#146;s
management, including the Chief Executive Officer and Chief Accounting Officer, on the effectiveness of the design and operation of the Company&#146;s disclosure controls and procedures (as defined in Rules
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">13a-15(e)</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">15d-15(e)</FONT> under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934). Based on that evaluation, the Company&#146;s management, including the Chief Executive Officer and
Chief Accounting Officer, concluded that the Company&#146;s disclosure controls and procedures were effective as of December&nbsp;31, 2019. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Disclosure controls and procedures are the controls and other procedures that are designed to ensure that the information required to be
disclosed by the Company in its reports filed and submitted under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (&#147;Exchange Act&#148;) is recorded, processed, summarized and reported, within the time periods specified in the Securities and
Exchange Commission&#146;s rules and forms. Disclosure controls and procedures include, without limitation, controls and procedures designed to ensure that information required to be disclosed by the Company in its reports filed under the Exchange
Act is accumulated and communicated to the Company&#146;s management, including the principal executive officer and principal accounting officer, as appropriate to allow timely decisions regarding required disclosure. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; text-indent:9%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">During the quarter ended December&nbsp;31, 2019, no change in the Company&#146;s internal controls over financial reporting (as defined
in Rules <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">13a-15(f)</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">15d-15(f)</FONT> under the Exchange Act) has occurred that has materially affected, or is reasonably likely to materially affect, the Company&#146;s
internal controls over financial reporting. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">51 </P>

these matters will have no material effect on the consolidated operations or consolidated financial condition of WVS Financial Corp. </P>
